Jacobs’s Incidents in the Life of a Slave Girl, abolitionist print culture, courtroom witness testimony, and the work of Hortense Spillers, Moore shows how the logic of slavery and antiblack racism also dictates the silencing techniques of the contemporary domestic violence courtroom. By positioning testimony on contemporary domestic violence prosecution within the archive of slavery, Moore demonstrates that domestic violence and its image are haunted by black bodies, black flesh, and black freedom.Duke University Press Scholars of Color First Book Award recipient  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAfrican AmericansxSocial conditionsy19th century. 0aDiscrimination in justice administrationzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aFamily violencexLaw and legislationzUnited States. 0aLegal photographyzUnited States. 0aPhotographyxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aSlaveryxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aVictims of family violencexLegal status, laws, etczUnited States. 0aVictims of family violencexLegal status, laws, etc.zUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / African American Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076691240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478022947?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478022947423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781478022947/original  a978-3-11-076691-2  Duke University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles